     1	U.S. ROBOTICS SPORTSTER 14400 - AN UNINTENDED BARGAIN
     2	 -----------------------------------------------------
     3	
     4	Modem manufacturer U.S. Robotics has long offered two classes of modems, the
     5	Courier and the Sportster lines. Courier is the top of the line modem and
     6	within the BBS community is considered one of the top models available.
     7	Sportster modems were typically the ugly little brother - at a much more
     8	economical price.
     9	
    10	The company recently released some new Sportster models that have an allure.
    11	The Sportster 14000 and Sportster 14000 with Fax offer CCITT V.32bis
    12	connections at 14,400 bps, V.42 and V.42bis error correction and compression,
    13	Microcom Networking Protocol (MNP) level 5 compatibility, and in the case of
    14	the fax model - 9600 bps fax. The modems are listed at $519 and $549
    15	respectively - actually not terribly competitive in the economy class for
    16	modems with this functionality. But Sportsters are almost designed to be
    17	discounted and these are available on the street at around $290 which is
    18	quite competitive.
    19	
    20	The main difference between the Sportster models and the Courier models in
    21	this case is the case. The Courier features a very nice black plastic case
    22	suitable for framing. The Sportster looks like nothing so much as a Radio
    23	Shack home intercomm. You are almost drawn to press a switch, lean over to
    24	speak into it, and ask mom for some juice with this thing.
    25	
    26	But under the hood lies more modem than even U.S. Robotics apparently
    27	intended. The modem motherboard within is not similar to the $1295 Courier
    28	Dual Standard, it actually IS the Courier Dual Standard motherboard. The
    29	Courier Dual Standard of course, in addition to the 14.4kbps V.32bis mode,
    30	features a 16.8kbps proprietary HST  (High Speed Technology) mode, a really
    31	nice case, an ASL mode, and a list price of $1295. We obtained data transfer
    32	rates as high as 1885 cps with this top of the line model and reviewed it
    33	very favorably in our October issue.
    34	
    35	The reasons for this are fairly understandable. It is actually cheaper to
    36	manufacture lots of a single motherboard than two different motherboards. And
    37	by repackaging it in a downscale case and disabling a few features, you can
    38	reach an entirely different market segment without a lot of retooling.
    39	
    40	The difference in features is a function of the operating software held in
    41	Read-Only-Memory (ROM) chips on the modem motherboard. But on a large number
    42	of early shipments of the Sportster, the code is still in the ROMs, and can
    43	be reactivated with simple AT commands to give the lightweight Sportster the
    44	16.8Kbps mode that is the most notable function of the Courier power house.
    45	It does not appear to add the ASL function.
    46	
    47	To see if your model supports this, enter the command ATI7 to display the ROM
    48	version. At the bottom of the display, you should see an entry for SUPERVISOR
    49	VER 4.1 or SUPERVISOR VER 4.2. It will also list an OPTIONS V32 entry. If
    50	your ROM indicates SUPERVISOR VER 4.1, you win the USR Sweepstakes. Enter the
    51	command AT GW 03C6,22 GW 05CD,2F and again enter ATI7. The options entry
    52	should now read OPTIONS HST,V32. This means you can now use the 16.8kbps HST
    53	mode. The ATB1 command will turn it on. And if you dial a BBS with a Courier
    54	Dual Standard, you will get a 16800/ARQ connect.
    55	
    56	Currently shipping models of the Sportster have a version 4.2 ROM and the
    57	command doesn't work. Merry Christmas from U.S. Robotics. Rumor has it there
    58	are some very unhappy campers within USR over this marketing faux pas. We
    59	don't get it. So some USR customers got a good deal - that's got to be
    60	terrible PR right?
    61	
    62	Apparently USR is determined to turn it into a negative one way or another.
    63	The company has issued a fairly artless written IMPORTANT WARNING TO BULLETIN
    64	BOARD USERS quoting chapter and verse of U.S. copyright law. We produce the
    65	full text of this warning here:
    66	
    67	"IMPORTANT WARNING TO BULLETIN BOARD USERS:
    68	
